[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.10: Clinical Trial Recruitment Conversationalist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per engaged candidate (depends on study portfolio breadth, screening depth, channel mix, model choice, RAG corpus depth, and IRB-approval-tracking overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is Tuesday at 7:42 PM. Maria is 58. Maria has stage-IV non-small-cell lung cancer with an EGFR exon 19 deletion, has been on a targeted therapy for the last fourteen months, has had a partial response that has plateaued, and is now starting to see slow progression on her last two scans. Maria's oncologist has had the conversation with her about second-line options. The standard-of-care path is reasonable but not exciting. The oncologist has also mentioned, almost in passing, that there are clinical trials Maria might want to consider, including one local trial of a next-generation EGFR inhibitor and one trial of a bispecific antibody plus chemotherapy that is enrolling at an academic center about ninety minutes away. Maria's oncologist is genuinely supportive of trial options, has done the right thing by raising them, and has handed Maria a folder with two pamphlets and the phone number of a research coordinator. The conversation took about six minutes at the end of a thirty-minute appointment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria gets home, makes dinner, sits with the folder for the rest of the evening. The pamphlets are professional, clearly produced, and approximately incomprehensible. The first pamphlet says the trial is a "phase 1b/2 dose-escalation and dose-expansion study of MK-7339 in combination with pembrolizumab in patients with advanced NSCLC harboring EGFR-activating mutations who have progressed on a tyrosine kinase inhibitor with documented T790M-negative status and ECOG performance status of 0 or 1." Maria has read this sentence four times and is reasonably sure that some of the words apply to her, but cannot tell which ones. The second pamphlet, for the bispecific trial, has similar language plus a detailed schedule of pharmacokinetic blood draws, a description of mandatory tumor biopsies at screening and at progression, an explanation of dose-limiting toxicities and the dose-escalation cohorts, and a list of about thirty-seven exclusion criteria including several Maria recognizes from her medical history and several she does not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria is, in absolute terms, well-positioned to consider clinical trials. She has insurance, transportation, a supportive family, an oncologist who values trials, English fluency, and a graduate degree. She has access to internet research, has used MyChart for years, and is reasonably comfortable making phone calls to medical offices during business hours. She is, in clinical-trial-recruitment terms, a high-likelihood prospective participant. Maria still does not enroll in either trial. Maria does not enroll in the local trial because she calls the research coordinator's phone number on Wednesday morning at 9:15 AM, gets a voicemail, leaves a message, does not hear back for three days, calls again on the following Tuesday, gets the same voicemail, leaves another message, hears back on Thursday from a coordinator who is helpful but is in the middle of a different consent conversation and asks if Maria can come in for a screening visit on the following Monday at 10 AM, which Maria cannot because she has chemotherapy at her oncologist's office that morning, and the coordinator says they will reschedule and call back, and the coordinator does not call back for two weeks. By the time Maria has rescheduled, her oncologist has started Maria on the standard second-line regimen because the slow progression is no longer slow, and Maria is now ineligible for the trial because she has received an interceding line of therapy. Maria does not enroll in the academic-center trial because the screening visit is ninety minutes away, the trial coordinator is helpful on the phone but cannot answer questions about insurance coverage or reimbursement for travel, the consent document is forty-three pages, and Maria cannot quite figure out from the consent document or from the phone call whether the experimental therapy will be administered at the academic center (with a ninety-minute drive each way every two weeks for at least six months) or whether some of the visits can be done at her local infusion center. Maria is exhausted. The standard regimen is right there. The standard regimen, even though Maria knows from her oncologist that the response rate is modest, is what she goes with.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Maria's story is the typical story. The percentage of cancer patients in the U.S. who participate in clinical trials is small, in the low single digits across most cancer types. <!-- TODO: verify; estimates of cancer-clinical-trial participation rates in the U.S. typically range from 3% to 8% depending on cancer type, disease setting, and population, with substantial disparities by race, ethnicity, age, geography, and socioeconomic status; the National Cancer Institute, the Coalition for Clinical Trials Awareness, and academic literature publish updated figures --> The participation gap is not because the trials would not benefit those patients. Many of the trials would. The participation gap is the product of a recruitment pipeline that, end to end, is operationally broken at almost every step. Patients do not know which trials exist for their condition. The trials' eligibility criteria are written for protocol committees and not for patients. The recruitment communication is constrained by IRB-approved scripts that are, by design, not particularly engaging. The research coordinators who do the recruitment work are scarce, are often spread across many studies, are reachable mostly during business hours, and have no good way to triage prospective participants quickly. The screening visits are time-intensive and expensive, and the no-show rate for screening visits is, by some measures, high enough that coordinators rationally over-recruit and tolerate dropoff. The patients who navigate the recruitment pipeline successfully are disproportionately the ones with the most personal resources, which is part of why clinical trials are non-representative of the populations they are meant to serve, which is part of why drug-approval evidence has known generalizability problems for non-trial-represented populations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cost of this is large. For drug developers, the most expensive line item in clinical development is often patient recruitment; trials that miss enrollment timelines cost hundreds of millions in extended development time. <!-- TODO: verify; clinical-trial recruitment delays are widely documented as a leading driver of drug-development cost overruns; specific figures vary by therapeutic area, trial size, and source --> For research institutions, the cost is in unenrolled trials, frustrated coordinators, and lost academic productivity. For patients, the cost is the absence of access to potentially better therapies, in some cases including therapies they could have had if the recruitment workflow had not been broken at the moment they were ready to consider it. For population science, the cost is non-representative trial cohorts and the resulting evidence-base limitations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generations of recruitment-improvement attempts have been incremental: better trial-finder websites (which raised the awareness ceiling but did not improve the conversion-to-enrollment funnel much), automated EHR-based prescreening (which produces lists of candidates faster than coordinators can call them), centralized recruitment vendors (which improved scale at some cost in patient experience), and direct-to-consumer recruitment campaigns (which fill some trials but skew toward the most online and most resourced patients). Each helped at the margin. None of them changed the basic shape of the workflow: a candidate has to encounter a trial, has to translate a complicated protocol into language that applies to their situation, has to figure out their basic eligibility, has to decide whether to invest the time and travel for a screening visit, has to navigate the screening visit's logistics, has to read and understand a long consent document, and has to do all of this on the coordinator's schedule rather than on their own.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about a conversational AI tool that addresses the candidate-facing portion of this workflow. It is not the IRB. It is not the protocol. It is not the consent. It is not the coordinator. It is the layer between the patient (or the patient's caregiver, or the referring clinician's MA) and the recruitment pipeline, the layer that takes a patient who has been told a trial exists, or who has searched for trials for their condition, or who has clicked an ad, and helps them figure out whether the trial is plausibly relevant to their situation, which questions they have, what they should expect from a screening visit, what the time and travel commitment looks like, and how to actually reach a coordinator at a time that works for both of them. The bot does not consent the patient. The bot does not enroll the patient. The bot does not do the eligibility determination that licensed clinical research staff have to do. The bot accelerates the candidate-facing steps of the funnel that have, historically, been bottlenecked on coordinator availability and on the gap between protocol language and patient language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the bot that engages prospective participants in conversation to surface candidate trials, explain study elements in patient-friendly language grounded in IRB-approved content, conduct prescreening using IRB-approved questions, surface scheduling availability for screening visits, hand off warm to research coordinators with conversation context attached, and (where appropriate) maintain a relationship with prospective participants who are not currently eligible but may become eligible later.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a consent tool. The bot does not consent participants. Informed consent is a regulated, documented, in-person (or carefully validated remote) clinical research staff function that the bot supports but does not replace.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not an eligibility determiner. The bot does prescreening using IRB-approved questions. Eligibility determination is a clinical research staff function that uses chart review, screening labs, screening imaging, and clinician judgment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a recruitment-only tool with no clinical research staff. The bot is deployed as part of a research operation that includes coordinators, principal investigators, clinical research nurses, regulatory staff, and an IRB. A bot deployed without that backstop is a bot operating outside the regulated workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a marketing tool. Recruitment communication is regulated. IRB-approved language is required for patient-facing communication about a study. The bot's recruitment content is reviewed by the IRB. The bot does not freestyle recruitment language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not an enrollment-quota tool. A bot evaluated only on the number of candidates who become enrolled participants will be optimized for the wrong thing, will pressure candidates inappropriately, and will erode patient trust. The bot is evaluated on the appropriateness of candidate-trial matches, the quality of the candidate's understanding of the trial, the candidate's reported satisfaction with the recruitment experience, and the conversion from screening to enrollment among candidates who got to the screening visit (where conversion is a function of the trial fit, not just of the bot's persuasion).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a sponsor-driven content surface. The recruitment material is the institution's IRB-approved material, not the sponsor's marketing material. Sponsor-funded recruitment is allowed and is common, but the patient-facing language is the IRB-approved language.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-trial-at-a-time tool. A patient often has multiple potentially-relevant trials open at any given time, across multiple sponsors, multiple sites, and multiple eligibility profiles. The bot's matching is across the institution's open-trial portfolio (and where appropriate, federated to partner-institution portfolios), not against a single trial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the patient's relationship with their treating clinician. Trial enrollment decisions are made in collaboration with the patient's oncologist, neurologist, cardiologist, or whichever specialist is treating the underlying condition. The bot supports the conversation; the bot does not replace it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the bot's value lives in three places. First, in the candidate-facing translation layer (turning protocol language into patient language, with citation grounding so the institutional content is preserved). Second, in the operational compression of the recruitment funnel (moving candidates through awareness-to-prescreen-to-coordinator-handoff faster than the previous workflow, with fewer coordinator-touchpoints required for the early stages, and with the coordinator's time concentrated on the candidates who are most likely to benefit). Third, in the equity-of-access lift, when designed carefully (enabling candidates who would not otherwise have made it through the recruitment funnel to do so, by removing scheduling, language, and complexity barriers that disproportionately filter out under-represented populations). A bot evaluated only on enrollment volume misses two of the three. A bot designed only to fill enrollment quotas erodes patient trust and produces non-representative cohorts. A bot designed for the funnel-compression and equity-of-access lifts, with appropriate IRB and regulatory governance, does work that the previous workflow could not do and creates value that aligns with both the institution's research mission and the patient's interests.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[K
