[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Conversational Trial Matching Grounded In IRB-Approved Content, Eligibility Logic, and Coordinator Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Clinical-Trial Recruitment Has Resisted Digital Tools, and Why The Latest Attempts Are Different
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical-trial recruitment, as a workflow, has been bottlenecked at the same place for thirty years: the gap between protocol language (which is written for the IRB, the FDA, and the protocol committee) and patient language (which is what the candidate actually needs in order to decide whether to invest the time to find out more). The standard solution has been the IRB-approved patient-facing recruitment material (a one-page flier, a four-page brochure, a website description) which translates the protocol into something more readable but cannot, structurally, answer the candidate's specific question about their specific situation. The candidate's question is always shaped by what the candidate has been through and what they are deciding now. The IRB-approved material is shaped by what the protocol committee considered patient-relevant six months ago when they wrote it. The two do not meet without a person in the middle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The person in the middle has been, traditionally, the research coordinator. The research coordinator is, in most institutions, a registered nurse or a clinical research professional with training in good clinical practice (GCP), with deep familiarity with the protocols they recruit for, and with a queue of prospective candidates that often exceeds their capacity to reach by phone in a timely way. The coordinator's expertise is real and is hard to replicate. The coordinator's bandwidth is finite. The cost of the bandwidth limit shows up in the numbers: a candidate who calls a coordinator at 9 AM on Tuesday and reaches voicemail will, with measurable probability, not make it to a screening visit; a candidate who reaches a coordinator on the first attempt is meaningfully more likely to enroll. Coordinator availability, in other words, is one of the dominant predictors of whether a candidate makes it from awareness to enrollment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that has changed is the same thing that changed the other patient-facing bot use cases in this chapter: large language models that can carry on a coherent, scoped, IRB-content-grounded conversation with a candidate, that can ask the prescreening questions the candidate is going to be asked anyway, that can explain protocol language in patient-friendly terms while staying inside IRB-approved content, that can connect the candidate to scheduling and coordinator handoff, and that are available at the moment the candidate is ready to engage rather than at the moment the coordinator's calendar permits. The bot is not the coordinator. The bot is a layer between the candidate and the coordinator that does the translation work and the prescreening work that, in the previous workflow, was bottlenecked on coordinator-availability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "candidate calls coordinator and coordinator takes them through prescreening at the coordinator's pace" to "candidate engages the bot at the candidate's pace and the bot collects prescreening data, contextualizes the trial, and arranges the coordinator handoff with full context attached." The bot does not eliminate the coordinator. The bot moves the coordinator's bandwidth to where the bandwidth has the most value (informed-consent conversations, eligibility-determination judgment, complex candidate questions, study management) and away from where the bandwidth was being wasted (initial inquiry calls, voicemail tag, prescreening-question repetition, scheduling logistics).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on the recruitment-AI category. The careful end of the spectrum is institutionally-deployed bots that engage candidates with IRB-approved content, conduct IRB-approved prescreening, route to institutional coordinators, and operate within the institution's regulated research workflow. The middle of the spectrum is sponsor-direct or recruitment-vendor-direct tools that operate outside the institution's workflow, sometimes with appropriate institutional partnership and sometimes without. The risky end of the spectrum is recruitment tools that pressure candidates, that misrepresent trial requirements, that conduct eligibility-determination using bot logic alone, that use deceptive marketing patterns, or that operate without IRB awareness or approval of the patient-facing content. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA, OHRP, and major institutional research-protection programs have published guidance on AI-mediated recruitment; the regulatory and ethics literature on AI-mediated recruitment continues to evolve --> This recipe is firmly in the careful end. The architectural decisions reflect that.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Trial-Recruitment Bot Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A trial-recruitment bot, as designed in this recipe, is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that scopes it to recruitment-and-prescreening (and not to eligibility-determination, consent, enrollment, or general medical advice), the candidate's authenticated context (where the candidate is engaging through an authenticated patient portal or through a logged-in trial-search experience), or anonymous context (where the candidate is engaging through a public-facing trial-search experience), access to the institution's open-trial portfolio with IRB-approved patient-facing content per trial, access to the per-trial prescreening question set (each set IRB-approved), and a careful set of tools for searching the trial portfolio, surfacing IRB-approved content, conducting prescreening, scheduling screening visits, escalating to a coordinator, and (where the candidate has consented) collecting limited candidate context for inclusion in the coordinator handoff.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The conversation surface is not one conversation. It is a stream of conversational episodes. Some episodes start with a candidate asking about a specific trial they have heard of from their treating clinician. Some start with a candidate searching by condition ("I have stage IV lung cancer with an EGFR mutation, what trials are open?"). Some start from a referring clinician's office where the MA is helping the patient explore options between visits. Some start from an outreach SMS or email that the institution sent in response to a candidate's prior expression of interest. Some are anonymous (the candidate has not authenticated, has not provided contact information, is just looking around).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Discovery.** The candidate enters the conversation with a question, a condition, a trial name, or a referral. The bot responds with the candidate-relevant set of open trials at the institution (filtered by condition, by population, by site location where the candidate is willing to travel, and by basic public-eligibility criteria), drawn from the institution's recruitment-content corpus. Each trial is summarized in IRB-approved patient-facing language, with the IRB-approved short description, the eligibility outline, the time and visit commitment, the expected interventions, and the contact pathway to a coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Translation.** When the candidate has questions about a specific trial ("what does T790M-negative mean?", "what is a phase 1b/2 dose escalation?", "what is ECOG performance status?"), the bot answers in patient-friendly terms drawn from the IRB-approved content corpus or from a glossary that the institution maintains for cross-trial concepts. The translation is grounded; the bot does not freestyle medical content.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prescreening.** The bot offers, with explicit framing as voluntary and as not-an-eligibility-determination, the per-trial prescreening question set. The prescreening question set is IRB-approved, is no longer than necessary, and is presented in conversational form. The bot collects the candidate's answers, runs them against the per-trial prescreening logic (deterministic rule evaluation, not LLM judgment), and produces a prescreening result that is one of: "this trial appears to be a possible fit and a coordinator can talk to you about a screening visit," "this trial does not appear to be a fit based on what you've told me, and here are some alternative trials," or "we need a coordinator to help with this question, would you like a call?". The bot is explicit that the prescreening is not the same as the eligibility determination that happens at a screening visit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Logistics.** The bot answers candidate questions about the time and travel commitment, the visit schedule, the location of visits, whether visits can be done at the candidate's local infusion center vs. only at the academic site, whether the trial covers the experimental drug, whether there is reimbursement for travel, what the side-effect profile is per the IRB-approved content, what the placebo or standard-of-care comparator looks like, and what happens if the candidate decides to leave the trial. Each answer is grounded in the IRB-approved content for that trial.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator handoff.** When the candidate has a question outside the bot's scope, when the candidate wants to schedule a screening visit, when the candidate has a positive prescreening result and wants to proceed, when the candidate has a complex situation that the bot cannot handle, or when the candidate just wants to talk to a person, the bot routes to the institution's research-coordinator workforce. The handoff is warm: the conversation context, the prescreening result if any, the candidate's stated preferences, and the candidate's contact information (if the candidate has provided it) are attached to the handoff so the coordinator can pick up the conversation rather than starting over.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Standing-queue maintenance.** Some candidates are interested but not eligible right now (a trial may not be enrolling, the candidate may need to wait until they have progressed on standard therapy, the candidate may be eligible for a future cohort). The bot maintains, with the candidate's consent, a candidate-of-interest list that re-engages when an appropriate trial opens or the candidate's eligibility window changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-of-access support.** The bot provides multilingual support, accessible interface support, and an explicit framing that participation is the candidate's choice and that the candidate has the right to ask any question. The bot's design specifically targets the populations who have historically been under-represented in trials (linguistic minorities, racial and ethnic minorities, older adults, rural residents, candidates without easy access to academic centers).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-boarding.** Some candidates decide not to pursue trials, decide to enroll in a trial elsewhere, or have completed their decision. The bot supports a respectful exit with no pressure, with clear path back if the candidate changes their mind, and with consent-revocation for any data the candidate has shared.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Trial-Recruitment Bot
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, point it at a public clinical-trials database (such as ClinicalTrials.gov), give it a chat surface, prompt it with "you are a helpful clinical-trial assistant," and let it engage candidates. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has regulatory, ethical, and operational consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no IRB-approval awareness.** Patient-facing recruitment content, in the U.S., is regulated by 21 CFR 50, 21 CFR 56, and the Common Rule (45 CFR 46). The IRB approves patient-facing content for each trial. A bot that freestyles recruitment language using whatever the LLM produces is a bot that is delivering non-IRB-approved content to candidates, which is a regulatory violation. The bot delivers from the IRB-approved content corpus per trial; the bot does not freestyle recruitment language. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance and OHRP guidance on patient-facing recruitment content includes IRB review of recruitment material; specific regulatory citations and interpretation vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no per-trial-content versioning.** Recruitment content changes when the protocol amends, when the IRB requires revisions, when sponsors update the content, or when the trial closes a cohort. The bot's content store has versioning per trial, with effective dates, expiration dates, and IRB-approval-ID provenance. Without this, the bot will, at some point, deliver outdated recruitment material that has been superseded.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of eligibility-determination scope.** Eligibility for a clinical trial is determined by clinical research staff using chart review, screening labs, screening imaging, and clinician judgment. Prescreening, conducted by the bot using IRB-approved questions, is a different thing. The bot does not say "you are eligible." The bot says "your responses suggest this trial is a possible fit; the coordinator will determine eligibility at the screening visit." Conflating prescreening with eligibility determination is a regulatory and ethical error.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent scope.** Informed consent for a clinical trial is a regulated process with specific requirements. The bot does not consent the candidate. The bot can describe what consent will involve at a coordinator visit, can answer general questions about the consent process, and can route consent-related questions to a coordinator. The bot does not produce a consent document, does not collect a signature, and does not interpret the candidate's consent preferences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of vulnerable populations.** Some populations have specific protections in research (children, prisoners, pregnant individuals, decisionally-impaired candidates, employees of the sponsor or institution). The bot's prescreening, content surfacing, and coordinator routing accounts for these. <!-- TODO: verify; vulnerable-population protections in research are codified in 45 CFR 46 Subparts B, C, and D; specific protections vary by population --> A bot that engages a self-identified minor with adult-trial content, or that prescreens an adult under guardianship without acknowledging the consent posture, is producing problems for the institution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model invents trial information when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling trial details, eligibility criteria, dose schedules, or side-effect profiles is delivering content the institution and the IRB have not approved. The trial-content RAG with strict citation grounding is the architectural floor; the LLM delivers information from the IRB-approved corpus, not from its parametric memory of clinical literature.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of pressure or coercion.** Recruitment communication that pressures candidates, that uses urgency tactics, that emphasizes investigator enthusiasm in ways that bias the candidate's decision, or that downplays risk is regulated against. The bot's tone, language, and pacing are reviewed by the IRB and by the institutional research-integrity office. The system prompt, the output safety, and the sampled-review process all enforce non-pressuring patterns.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of concomitant-medication and washout-period content.** Many trials have inclusion or exclusion criteria related to current medications, recent therapy lines, and washout periods between therapies. Patient-friendly translation of this content has to be precise; an imprecise translation can lead a candidate to either over-include themselves (they think they are eligible when they are not) or over-exclude themselves (they think they are not eligible when they are). The bot delivers IRB-approved patient-friendly translations; the bot does not translate eligibility criteria on the fly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of competing-trial fairness.** Many institutions run multiple trials that may overlap in eligible-population. Coordinators are bound by institutional and IRB policies on candidate-presentation order and trial-selection neutrality. The bot's matching logic respects institutional policy on trial-presentation order; the bot does not promote one trial over another for non-clinical reasons.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of reportable events during recruitment.** A candidate disclosing a serious adverse event, a candidate disclosing intent to deceive the trial about their eligibility, a candidate disclosing a complaint about a previous research experience, or a candidate in a research-related crisis triggers institutional reporting workflows. The bot recognizes the categories and routes appropriately. <!-- TODO: verify; institutional reporting requirements during recruitment vary by event category and by institution; specific workflows are governed by institutional research-protection policies -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to research data.** Pre-screening data the candidate provides is governed by HIPAA when collected by a covered entity, by the Common Rule when used for research purposes, and by GDPR or state privacy laws where applicable. Data minimization, retention scoping, candidate-revocation, and downstream use restrictions are non-trivial. The institutional research-protection program reviews the data-handling posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of sponsor-vs-institution boundary.** The institution conducts the trial; the sponsor funds it. Patient-facing content is IRB-approved, not sponsor-approved (though the sponsor often participates in content development). Sponsors are not direct recipients of candidate-identified data unless and until appropriate consents are in place. The bot's data flow respects this boundary.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when to stop recruiting.** When a trial closes a cohort, when a trial reaches enrollment, when the IRB suspends a trial, or when the institution pauses recruitment for any reason, the bot stops surfacing the trial immediately. The mechanism is tied to the institution's trial-management system, not to the bot's content corpus refresh schedule.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of multi-site trials and site-specific differences.** A single trial may be enrolling at multiple sites with different schedules, different sub-investigator availability, and different cohorts. The bot's per-trial content includes site-specific variants where they exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of equity calibration.** A bot that recruits efficiently from candidates with the most personal resources and least efficiently from candidates with structural barriers (language, transportation, working hours, comfort with digital tools) makes the existing trial-non-representativeness problem worse. The bot's per-cohort monitoring includes recruitment-funnel-by-demographic-cohort metrics, with explicit equity targets and per-cohort review by clinical-research leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Trial-Recruitment Bot Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.9 establish the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening, scope discipline, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, prompt-injection defense, citation grounding, longitudinal-context loading where appropriate, graceful degradation. The trial-recruitment bot adds seven structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approval discipline as architectural primitive.** The recruitment-content corpus per trial is IRB-approved, version-controlled, effective-dated, and provenance-tagged with the IRB-approval-ID. The bot delivers from this corpus only. Content updates flow through IRB review before they appear in the bot. The pipeline from IRB approval to bot deployment is auditable and traceable.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prescreening-vs-eligibility-determination scope discipline.** Prescreening is the bot's territory; eligibility determination is the coordinator's. The bot's language is consistent on this distinction. The output safety detects and corrects responses that imply eligibility-determination beyond prescreening.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial-portfolio integration with the institution's CTMS.** The bot's content corpus and trial-status indicators are sourced from the institution's clinical trial management system (CTMS) or equivalent system of record, not maintained as a separate copy. Trial closures, enrollment pauses, and amendments propagate to the bot through the CTMS integration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-workforce integration as primary handoff architecture.** The bot is deployed alongside the institution's research-coordinator workforce. The handoff is warm, with conversation context attached, with the candidate's prescreening result, and with the candidate's stated preferences. Capacity sizing is part of the deployment-readiness gate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recruitment-content-pressure-and-tone discipline.** Recruitment communication has specific regulatory and ethical constraints around tone, pressure, and presentation. The bot's tone is reviewed by the IRB and by the institutional research-integrity office. Sampled review specifically tags pressure-tone, urgency-bias, and risk-minimization as failure modes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-of-access measurement as primary outcome metric.** The bot's value is measured in part by its ability to lift recruitment-funnel conversion for under-represented populations. Per-cohort recruitment-funnel metrics (awareness-to-prescreen, prescreen-to-coordinator-handoff, coordinator-handoff-to-screening-visit, screening-visit-to-enrollment) are monitored with explicit equity targets.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Standing-queue maintenance with consent-revocability.** The bot maintains, with the candidate's consent, a candidate-of-interest list. Candidates can revoke consent and have their data removed at any time. The standing-queue logic respects consent-revocation immediately.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes: tool-surface contract management, identity-assurance lifecycle, conversation logging, per-cohort monitoring, graceful degradation when upstream systems fail.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Clinical-Research Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes trial recruitment specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The institutional research-protection program is a primary stakeholder, not a checkbox.** The IRB, the human research protection program (HRPP), the institutional research-integrity office, and the research-compliance office are all involved in the bot's design, content, and ongoing operation. Most institutions have not deployed AI-mediated recruitment before, so the institutional posture is being developed alongside the bot. <!-- TODO: verify; institutional research-protection-program approaches to AI-mediated recruitment are a developing area; specific institutional postures vary -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The trial-content lifecycle is multi-stakeholder.** The protocol team, the sponsor, the IRB, the institutional research-integrity office, the patient-experience team, and the clinical-research-leadership are all participants in the recruitment-content lifecycle. A change to recruitment content typically takes weeks to flow through; a change to the bot's delivery of that content takes minutes. The integration between these two clocks is what the institutional governance is designed to handle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Prescreening logic is study-specific and is non-trivial.** Each trial's prescreening question set, scoring logic, and disposition mapping is custom. The institutional CTMS or trial-management platform is the system of record; the bot consumes prescreening logic from that system rather than reimplementing it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-condition portfolios make matching non-trivial.** A candidate with stage IV lung cancer may be relevant for ten institutional trials, two of which have cohorts open right now, with cohort-specific eligibility variations. The matching is done with deterministic logic on candidate-stated information against per-trial prescreening logic, not LLM judgment. The bot surfaces the matches; the coordinator validates them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Vulnerable-population handling is non-optional and is condition-specific.** Trials enrolling minors, prisoners, pregnant individuals, decisionally-impaired candidates, or members of the institution's own staff have specific protections. The bot's eligibility flow handles these with institution-specific policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recruiting under-represented populations requires more than translation.** Cultural fit, trust-building, community-partnership context, and historical-injustice acknowledgment are components of recruiting communities that have been harmed by past research practices. The bot's tone, content, and design accounts for this; the institutional community-engagement and patient-advocacy teams are part of the development cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The candidate's treating clinician is a primary stakeholder in most cases.** Most trial enrollments are coordinated with the candidate's treating clinician (their oncologist, neurologist, cardiologist, etc.). The bot supports the conversation between candidate and clinician, surfaces information the candidate can take to their next appointment, and (with consent) routes summaries to the treating clinician's care team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Dropout and withdrawal questions come up in recruitment, not just in enrollment.** Candidates ask, before they enroll, what happens if they want to leave the trial. The bot has IRB-approved language for this; the bot makes clear that withdrawal is the candidate's right.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation and reimbursement questions come up frequently.** Candidates ask about compensation for participation, about reimbursement for travel, about insurance coverage of the experimental therapy and of the standard-of-care components, and about coverage of toxicity management. The bot has IRB-approved language for this; the bot can route specific insurance questions to the coordinator or to a financial counselor.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Conflict-of-interest disclosures are part of recruitment content.** The protocol's conflict-of-interest disclosures (PI's relationships with the sponsor, sponsor's relationships with the institution, etc.) are part of the IRB-approved recruitment content. The bot surfaces them when the candidate asks, when the candidate is approaching a decision point, or per institutional policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcomes for candidates who do not enroll matter.** Most candidates who engage the bot will not enroll in a trial. The bot's value includes the candidates who explored options, decided trials were not right for them, and went forward with their treatment with better information. The bot's outcome measurement should not pathologize non-enrollment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcomes for candidates who do enroll are tracked through the CTMS and are not the bot's responsibility.** Once a candidate becomes an enrolled participant, the bot's role transitions from recruitment-facing to (in some institutions) study-participant-facing or to (in most institutions) handoff-and-exit. The bot is not a study-monitoring tool unless explicitly extended for that purpose.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability and risk exposure includes regulatory exposure.** A bot that delivers misrepresented trial information, conducts unauthorized eligibility determination, or recruits in ways that violate IRB-approved language exposes the institution to regulatory action, study suspension, and (in worst cases) FDA inspection findings. The institutional risk and compliance teams are part of the policy review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Centralized trial-finder platforms exist but have limited recruitment-funnel impact.** Public trial-finders (the federal ClinicalTrials.gov registry and others) raise awareness but do not solve the candidate-facing prescreening, translation, and coordinator-handoff problem. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov is the primary U.S. trial registry maintained by the National Library of Medicine; trial-finder usability and recruitment-conversion has been studied in peer-reviewed literature with mixed results -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor-direct and recruitment-vendor channels are common but vary in institutional integration.** Sponsors and recruitment vendors increasingly run direct-to-consumer recruitment campaigns. Institutional integration with these channels varies, with some institutions partnering closely and others maintaining a strict institutional-only posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **EHR-based prescreening and identification tools have improved.** Modern prescreening platforms identify candidates from EHR data, surface trial matches to the candidate's care team, and (in some cases) trigger candidate-facing outreach. The bot integrates with these as a candidate-facing channel.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FHIR-based research data integration is maturing.** The Vulcan Accelerator (HL7's research-focused FHIR accelerator) and the Research Subject FHIR resources support research-context data exchange. Where institutions have FHIR-native research data, the bot can consume candidate context with appropriate consent. <!-- TODO: verify; HL7 FHIR resources for research including ResearchStudy, ResearchSubject, and the Vulcan Accelerator's profiles are documented at hl7.org and vulcan.fhir.org; specific implementation status varies -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Validated patient-friendly translation libraries exist for some content categories.** Glossaries, plain-language summaries, and patient-friendly content libraries (such as those produced by the National Cancer Institute's PDQ and similar institutional efforts) are increasingly available. <!-- TODO: verify; the NCI's Physician Data Query (PDQ) and similar institutional patient-friendly content libraries are well-documented resources --> The bot's content includes references to validated translations where they exist.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA guidance on AI in clinical research is evolving.** The FDA's guidance on AI/ML-enabled software, on patient engagement in trials, and on decentralized clinical trials is continuing to develop. The institutional regulatory team tracks this. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA guidance on AI in clinical research includes documents on AI/ML-enabled SaMD, on patient engagement, and on decentralized clinical trials; specific document status varies -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle recruitment well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to recruitment. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve trial content, run prescreening logic, schedule coordinator handoffs, register candidate-of-interest preferences, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-focused recruitment tools have shown promise but are early.** Recruitment tools designed specifically for under-represented populations, in partnership with community organizations and with cultural-fit content development, have shown promise in pilot studies. The architectural patterns are similar to general recruitment bots, with deeper community and cultural-fit investment. <!-- TODO: verify; equity-focused recruitment-tool studies in published literature show variable results depending on program design -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer trial-recruitment tools at academic-medical-center and sponsor scale, with CTMS integration, IRB-content management, prescreening-logic engines, and coordinator-handoff workflows. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for prescreening-logic, IRB-content management, or coordinator-workforce extensions, and integrate with the institution's existing research workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
